## Problem

`countDraftRelations` crashes with a 400 error when a content type has relations to other content types that don't have draft & publish enabled. The error happens because `getDeepPopulateDraftCount` applies a `publishedAt: { $null: true }` filter to ALL relation targets, but non-D&P types don't have a `publishedAt` attribute.

This means any content type with even a single relation to a non-D&P type will throw an error every time a user opens the edit view or tries to publish.

## Root cause

In `packages/core/content-manager/server/src/services/utils/populate.ts`, the `getDeepPopulateDraftCount` function iterates over all relation attributes and adds a `publishedAt` filter without checking whether the target content type actually supports draft & publish:

```ts
case 'relation': {
  // ...
  if (isVisibleAttribute(model, attributeName)) {
    populateAcc[attributeName] = {
      count: true,
      filters: { [PUBLISHED_AT_ATTRIBUTE]: { $null: true } },  // crashes for non-D&P targets
    };
  }
}
```

## Fix

Added a check using `hasDraftAndPublish()` on the target model before adding the `publishedAt` filter. If the target doesn't support D&P, the relation is skipped entirely since non-D&P content types can't have drafts by definition.

## Test plan

- Added a `Tag` content type with `draftAndPublish: false` to the existing test suite
- Added a `tag` relation from `Product` to `Tag`
- Added test that creates a product with a tag relation and verifies `countDraftRelations` returns 200 with a count of 0 (instead of crashing)

### What does it do?

Implements the [“Filter by State in Admin Content Manager” request ](https://feedback.strapi.io/customization/p/filter-by-state-in-admin-content-manager) for the Content Manager list view.

The following two files are modified:
```packages/core/content-manager/admin/src/utils/api.ts```

The `buildValidParams` function now transforms status filters from the URL query into top-level query parameters. e.g.

```tsx
// This filter query
{
  filters: {
    __status: {
      $eq: "published"
    },
    // ...other filters
  }
}
// Becomes this
{
  status: "published",
  // ...other filters
}
```
This allows us to leverage existing features of the content manager API without making substantial adjustments to the Filter component logic. 

`packages/core/content-manager/admin/src/pages/ListView/components/Filters.tsx`
If Draft & Publish is enabled on a content type, a "status" filter is injected. It uses the key `__status`, which cannot conflict with user-defined attributes.

### Why is it needed?

Responding to Strapi feedback.

### How to test it?
1. Open Content Manager, go to a collection type with Draft & Publish enabled.
2. Open Filters, select Status is Draft, verify only drafts are shown.
3. Select Status is Published, verify only published (and modified) entries are shown.
4. Combine with another filter and confirm both apply.
5. Select both draft and published, ensure no results are returned. 
6. Navigate to a collection type without Draft & Publish enabled, ensure no State filter is present.

### Related issue(s)/PR(s)

https://github.com/strapi/strapi/pull/24977 - This proposed solution does not work

### What does it do?

This updates the document-service result types in `document-engine.ts`

`FindOne` now uses `Params.FindOne<TContentTypeUID>` instead of `Params.FindFirst<TContentTypeUID>`, which aligns the result typing with the actual `strapi.documents(uid).findOne(...)` method signature.

### Why is it needed?

`findOne` and `findFirst` do not accept the same params. `findOne` requires a `documentId`, but its result type was still constrained with the `findFirst` param shape.

That mismatch made the type definitions inconsistent and could lead to incorrect TypeScript inference around `findOne` calls and wrappers that reuse `findOne` params.

### How to test it?

try this in any service
```
import { factories } from '@strapi/strapi';
import type { Modules } from '@strapi/types';

type BasicFindOneParams = Modules.Documents.ServiceParams<'api::basic.basic'>['findOne'];

const params: BasicFindOneParams = {
  documentId: '1',
  sort: {},
};

export default factories.createCoreService('api::basic.basic', ({ strapi }) => ({
  async customFindOne(params: BasicFindOneParams) {
    const result = await strapi.documents('api::basic.basic').findOne({
      ...params,
    });
    return result;
  },
}));
```
you should face not typing issues

This is a type-only change, so no runtime behavior changes are expected.

